Mushrooms With Pasta, Red Wine and Thyme


   From ``Hot Vegetables.''


   8 ounces dried penne, fusilli or other favorite pasta &QL; 
{ cup chopped parsley &QL; 
2 ounces imported Parmesan cheese &QL; 
1 tablespoon cornstarch &QL; 
Sauce (recipe follows) &QL; 
Salt and ground black pepper to taste &QL;


   Set aside pasta, parsley, cheese and cornstarch in separate
containers. Make Sauce. Recipe may be completed to this point as
long as 8 hours ahead.


   To complete the dish, grate cheese and combine cornstarch with
an equal amount of cold water. Bring 4 quarts water to a rapid
boil. Lightly salt the water, then cook the pasta according to
package instructions. When the pasta loses its raw texture, but is
still slightly firm, tip the pasta and the water into a colander.
Return pasta pot to the stove over high heat. Add Sauce and bring
to a low boil. Stir in a little of the cornstarch mixture to
slightly thicken Sauce. Return pasta to pot and stir to evenly
combine. Add salt and pepper. Transfer pasta to a heated serving
platter or dinner plates. Sprinkle with parsley and grated cheese.
Serve immediately. Makes 4 servings.


   Sauce


   2 small yellow onions, chopped &QL; 
4 garlic cloves, minced &QL; 
1{ pounds mushrooms (shiitake, portobello, chanterelle, cremini or
hedgehog) &QL; 
1 cup each: red wine and vegetable or chicken broth &QL; 
2 tablespoons oyster sauce &QL; 
1 tablespoon soy sauce &QL; 
2 teaspoons tomato paste &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: Asian chili sauce and sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme leaves &QL; 
6 tablespoons unsalted butter, divided &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste &QL;


   Place onions and garlic in separate containers. Discard stems
from shiitake and portobello mushrooms. Cut mushrooms into
\-inch-wide pieces. In small bowl, combine wine, broth, oyster
sauce, soy sauce, tomato paste, chili sauce, sugar and thyme.


   Place a 12-inch nonreactive (not cast-iron or aluminum) skillet
over medium heat. Add half the butter. When it is melted, add
onions. Saut onions until golden, about 15 minutes. Add remaining
butter, garlic and mushrooms. Cook mushrooms until they soften,
expel all their moisture and eventually become densely textured,
about 10 to 15 minutes. Add wine sauce, bring to a boil over medium
heat and cook until mushrooms begin to show above the sauce, about
6 minutes. Cool, transfer to a bowl, cover and refrigerate.


   Cajun Asian Ratatouille


   From Fusion Food Cookbook. This is a slightly different version
of ratatouille because the vegetables are marinated, grilled, then
simmered in a spicy Cajun sauce.


   2 yellow onions &QL; 
4 each: Japanese eggplants and small zucchini &QL; 
3 green bell peppers &QL; 
4 vine-ripened tomatoes &QL; 
East West Marinade (recipe follows) &QL; 
6 garlic cloves, finely minced &QL; 
2 tablespoons each: finely minced fresh ginger and olive oil &QL; 
\ cup fresh oregano leaves &QL; 
1 bunch thyme (tied into a bundle with kitchen string) &QL; 
1 cup chicken stock (preferably homemade) &QL; 
1 cup white wine &QL; 
2 tablespoons oyster sauce &QL; 
2 teaspoons tomato paste &QL; 
{ teaspoon sugar &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
Peel onions, then slice into \-inch-wide rings. Trim ends off
eggplant and zucchini; cut each lengthwise into 4 sections. Stem
and seed bell peppers; cut into 1-inch-wide strips. Discard tomato
stems; cut tomatoes into {-inch slices. Make East-West Marinade;
marinate vegetables 1 hour, rotating them every 20 minutes.


   Combine garlic, ginger and olive oil. In a small bowl, combine
oregano, thyme, stock, wine, oyster sauce, tomato paste and sugar.
If using a gas barbecue or indoor grill, preheat to medium (350
degrees). If using charcoal or wood, prepare a fire. When coals or
wood is ash-covered or the gas barbecue or indoor grill is
preheated, brush grill with oil, then place vegetables on grill.
Grill until they soften and begin to turn golden, turning
vegetables and brushing on more marinade every 5 minutes. Reserve
extra marinade.


   Remove vegetables from grill; cut into bite-size pieces.

Cranberry Fizz


   From ``Keeping Entertaining Simple'' by Martha Storey (Storey
Books, $9.95).


   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 quart each: cranberry juice, orange juice and club soda, chilled &QL; 
1 { cups vodka (optional) &QL; 
 &QL;


   Combine juices and vodka in a serving bowl; serve.


   Variation: Use a combination of pineapple juice and orange
juice, or try a mixture of grapefruit juice and orange juice. Add
fresh cranberries and orange slices to water and freeze in a tube
cake pan to make an ice ring; float the ice ring in the punch bowl
to keep punch cold. Makes 16 servings.


